                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Somebody noticed me!   <img src="images/smiles/icon_mrgreen.gif" alt="icon_mrgreen.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Arcady wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
In this case, mezzing in a group can change the duration of an LDoN drastically. With the group I normally play with, we can finish a normal LDoN in 35 to 40 minutes. With a pet, it drops to 25 minutes or less. In Hard LDoNs, it can turn an 85 minute win/90 minute loss into a 50 to 60 minute win. The DPS difference is amazing. Herein lies your problem. You say you might be willing to do it when you get to the higher levels, but if you don't do it at the lower levels, you will SUCK at doing it at the higher levels. Learn to control pets when they hit for less than 100 pershot. If you try to learn when they quad for 600 per shot, you will die too often to learn anything.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I'm only level 39 and I don't have LDON yet so I don't know much about how the adventures work or higher level play with an enchanter.
<br />

<br />
I do charm soloing.  Been in the basilisk caves at Jaggedpine recently.  Without the open space of my old charming grounds (maticors in Eastern Wastes) I've learned how useful the stun spells can be.  So I have been learning.  Thank you for the advice about higher level play.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />39 Enchanter</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
